Currently, the genus Panophrys contains 47 recognized species (AmphibaWeb 2020;
Lyu et al. 2020
), representing the largest genus within Asian horned toads. Nevertheless, the diversity of this genus is still dramatically underestimated.
Liu et al. (2018)
has proposed 41 cryptic species of Panophrys from China . But so far, only 12 species have been named (
Wang et al. 2017a
; Li et al. 2018;
Wang et al. 2019a
;
Wang et al. 2019b
;
Lyu et al. 2020
), while others remain undescribed, which calls for further taxonomic work on these cryptic toads. Particularly, it is worth noting that the cryptic species Megophrys sp6 and Megophrys sp7 proposed by
Liu et al. (2018)
were suggested to be the same species and was described as M. ( Pa. ) nanlingensis after detailed morphological examination (
Wang et al. 2019a
), indicating that the recognitions from molecular data still require validation from detailed morphological characteristics to substantiate (
Lyu et al. 2020
).

In this study, we performed detailed morphological examinations on a series of Panophrys specimens form eastern China (
). A portion of these specimens have been revealed as cryptic species by
Liu et al. (2018)
, i.e., Megophrys sp15 from northern Fujian , Megophrys sp18 from central Fujian , Megophrys sp20 from eastern Zhejiang , and Megophrys sp21 from northeastern Jiangxi . Our result is consistent with Liu et al. ’s (2018) previous proposal, substantiating the recognition of these four new species of Panophrys , which are consequently described in this work. In addition, based on considerations of morphological and mitochondrial DNA sequence variation, we found a more broadly geographical distribution of these four species than previously reported (
Liu et al. 2018
), providing valuable new information on the phylogeny, morphology, and biogeography of these cryptic species.

DNA sequences were aligned by the Clustal W algorithm with default parameters (
Thompson et al. 1997
) and trimmed with gaps partially deleted in MEGA 6 (
Tamura et al. 2013
). Two gene segments, 632 base pairs (bp) of CO1 and 536 bp of 16S, were concatenated seriatim into a 1168-bp sequence, and were further tested in jmodeltest v2.1.2 with Akaike and Bayesian information criteria, all resulting the best-fitting nucleotide substitution models of GTR+I+G. Sequenced data were analyzed using Bayesian Inference (BI) in MrBayes 3.2.4 (
Ronquist et al. 2012
). Two independent runs were conducted in the BI analysis, each of which was ran for 10,000,000 generations and sampled every 1000 generations with the first 25% samples were discarded as burn-in, resulting a potential scale reduction factor (PSRF) of <0.005. Mean genetic distances among all samples were calculated in MEGA 6 using the uncorrected p -distance model based on 16S gene.

External measurements were recorded for specimens of the unnamed new species, with digital calipers (Neiko 01407A Stainless Steel 6-Inch Digital Caliper) to the nearest 0.1 mm . These measurements were as follows: SVL (snout–vent length, from tip of snout to posterior margin of vent); HDL (head length, from tip of snout to the articulation of the jaw); HDW (head width, head width at the commissure of the jaws); SNT (snout length, from tip of snout to the anterior corner of the eye); IND (internasal distance, distance between nares); IOD (interorbital distance, minimum distance between upper eyelids); ED (eye diameter, from the anterior corner of the eye to posterior corner of the eye); TD (tympanum diameter, horizontal diameter of tympanum); TED (tympanum–eye distance, from anterior edge of tympanum to posterior corner of the eye); HND (hand length, from the proximal border of the outer palmar tubercle to the tip of digit III ); RAD (radius length, from the flexed elbow to the proximal border of the outer palmar tubercle); FTL (foot length, from distal end of shank to the tip of digit IV); TIB (tibia length, from the outer surface of the flexed knee to the heel). Sex was determined by secondary sexual characters, such as the presence of vocal sacs, nuptial pads, or spines in males and their absences in females (
Fei et al. , 2016
).

The samples from Daiyun Mountain Nature Reserve and Xiamen City, southern Fujian (samples ID 1–8 inTable 1 and
), are clustered into a clade with strong nodal support (BPP 1.00), among which samples 1–2 were proposed as a cryptic species Megophrys sp 18 in Liu et al. (2018)
. The phylogenetic placement of this clade remains unresolved due to the weak support, and the smallest p -distance divergences between this clade and other Panophrys species are 3.0–3.4% in 16S (with P. boettgeri ). These populations can be further distinguished from all congeners by a combination of distinctive morphological characters (see Taxonomic accounts below and Table 3 ). Therefore, the populations from southern Fujian represent a separately evolving lineage, which is described as a new species, below.

The samples from Fenghua City and Mt Tiantai, eastern Zhejiang (samples ID 9–14 inTable 1 and
), group into a clade with strong nodal support (BPP 1.00), among which samples 9–11 were proposed as a cryptic species Megophrys sp 20 in Liu et al. (2018)
. This clade is the sister taxon to Panophrys xianjuensis occurring in central Zhejiang (BPP 0.96), and the smallest p -distance divergences between this clade and other species are 2.1–2.3% in 16S (with P. xianjuensis ). These populations can be further distinguished from all congeners by a combination of distinctive morphological characters (see Taxonomic accounts below and Table 3 ). Therefore, the populations from eastern Zhejiang represent a separately evolving lineage, which is described as a new species, below.

The samples from the hilly area among Fujian , Jiangxi and Guangdong (samples 15–27 inTable 1 and
), are clustered into a clade with strong nodal support (BPP 1.00), among which samples 15–18 were proposed as a cryptic species Megophrys sp 15 in Liu et al. (2018)
. The phylogenetic placement of this clade remains unresolved due to the weak support, and the smallest p -distance divergences between this clade and other Panophrys species are 2.6–3.0% in 16S (with P. kuatunensis ). These populations can be further distinguished from all congeners by a combination of distinctive morphological characters (see Taxonomic accounts below and Table 3 ). Therefore, the populations from the hilly area among Fujian , Jiangxi , and Guangdong represent a separately evolving lineage, which is described as a new species, below.

